<catsoop-section>Instructions</catsoop-section>

1. Take two printouts in A4 size paper of the given sheet.

2. Now cut out the strips: Reflector B, Rotor I, Rotor II, Rotor III, Input/Output and Reflector C, Rotor IV, Rotor V.

3. Now take a cylinder and first take one of the strips from Reflector B or Reflector C and fold on a cylinder. Join their ends by glue. Don't fix it on the cylinder. Here we took a Reflector B strip.

4. Now take any 3 strips from Rotor I to V and fold around the cylinder right to the reflector strip. Here we took Rotor I to III strips.

5. At the right most side fold the Input/Output strip and join its end. Don't fix it.

<center>
<img src="COURSE/representation/paper_enigma/paper_enigma_6.png" alt="Paper Enigma Assembly" height="400"/>
</center>

6. Turn the reflector and Input/Output strip and confirm the grey line on them is aligned with each other.

7. Set any message key on three Rotors. Let us take here A, B, C from left to right rotor by rotating them.

8. Take any message say "CCL GANDHINAGAR". To encode this, take the first letter of our message 'C'. Now turn out one letter of the right most rotor towards yourself.

9. Now find the Input C and see the line where it goes through rotors to reflectors and then back to Input/Output. Record the output.

10. Rotate one letter towards you of the right most rotor for every input letter. If you get grey colour on the right most rotor then rotate the right most and middle rotor one letter towards you. If the letter on the middle rotor is shaded grey, turn all three rotors one step towards you.

11. So CCL becomes **AUM**. Follow the rules and encrypt the whole message.

12. Now decrypt the message using the same way.

<catsoop-section>What's Happening</catsoop-section>

Here every letter has a unique reflector path. By turning rotors, the same letter's encryption also would be changed. Again, turning rotors from the grey bar (notch) makes the encryption more complex.

So the same letters in the message will not have the same reflection â€” therefore it will be unique. While decrypting the message we follow the same loop and we get the original message.

This is similar to how the real Enigma machine worked during World War II. The Germans used it to send secret military messages, and it took brilliant mathematicians like **Alan Turing** to crack the code!

